 the educational component is important too linkedin ceo jeff weiner in a letter to employees writes that one of the main benefits of the merger will be “accelerating our objective to transform learning and development by deeply integrating the lyndacomlinkedin learning solution in office alongside some of the most popular productivity apps on the planet” weiner notes that six of lynda’s  most popular trainings are related to microsoft products since being purchased by linkedin last year lynda has already started offering customized ‘learning paths’ that allow users to for example ‘become a frontend web developer‘ by viewing  hours of videos it’s not hard to imagine how these could be purchased by microsoft enterprise customers and used to train employees for new roles one unnamed linkedin executive quoted in quartz mentions the idea of a ‘learning’ tab added to office that would allow subscribers to immediately get tutorials on the software they’re using right there in the program itself right now lynda charges users  per month for a premium individual plan with bulk plans available for businesses who want to train multiple employees integrating access into microsoft office could make learning cheaper for existing office subscribers but lynda’s not the only company providing webbased tutorials on microsoft products—or software development by giving lyndamicrosoft offerings an advantage over other companies that provide tech training the acquisition could also reduce competition in the online education marketplace—which could be bad for developers on the other hand microsoft could choose to emphasize training for its own technologies within lynda ignoring or minimizing support for other platforms like ios as microsoft has not yet outlined detailed plans for lynda this will be something for developers to watch going forward       related posts linkedin exec microsoft acquisition won’t slow opensourcing free xamarin training for your new year’s weekend att announces new developer tools and other ces 0 news hololens development kits will ship march  linkedin lyndacom microsoft training jimmy dee thank goodness linkedin is a pile of junk and hadn’t done lyndacom any favors lyndacom is indeed one of the best places to help young people and people getting started to gain a basic level of competence and confidence with complex software even medium complexity linkedin is a glorified facebook ripoff and inbox spam generator linkedin was alien to learning and procedural intelligence which was the foundation of lyndacom really hoping to see lyndacom become its own entity again and get linkedin’s meddlesome fingers out of the pie authors jeff prosise  posts paul ballard  posts john robbins 0 posts jeremy likness  posts jeffrey richter  posts john garland 0 posts jonathan wood  posts paul mehner  posts dave baskin  posts wintellectnow  posts rik robinson  posts keith rome 0 posts josh lane  posts sergio loscialo  posts wintellect  posts blaize stewart  posts josh carroll  posts noel stieglitz  posts mitch harpur  posts jason hill  posts tony sneed  posts eric greene  posts scott peterson  posts dave banister  posts kevin griffin  posts topicsnet framework android angular angularjs apple aspnet async azure c cloud conferences debugging docker f google headline hololens html imageonly ios javascript jounce mef microsoft microsoft azure mobile open source paraffin powershell prism silverlight sterling tfs typescript universal windows apps visual studio wcf windows 0 windows  windows azure windows installer windows phone wpf xamarin xamarin formsarchives archives select month june 0   may 0   april 0   march 0   february 0   january 0  0 december 0  0 november 0   october 0   september 0   august 0   july 0   june 0   may 0   april 0   march 0  0 february 0   january 0   december 0   november 0   october 0   september 0   august 0   july 0   june 0   may 0   april 0   march 0   february 0   january 0   december 0   november 0   october 0   sep